emiums","pos":[0,28]}]},{"content":"These premiums are most often used for overtime earnings that are paid in addition to the base earnings.","pos":[6472,6576]},{"content":"These earnings include any adjustments that are required by the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA).","pos":[6577,6673]},{"content":"The following information must be set up before you can pay regular-rate-of-pay premiums:","pos":[6674,6763]},{"content":"Work cycles and work periods","pos":[6769,6797]},{"content":"An earning code group that contains all earning codes for all nondiscretionary earnings","pos":[6802,6889]},{"pos":[6894,6996],"content":"Earning codes that use a rate basis of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Regular rate of pay<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to calculate and pay the premium amount","source":"Earning codes that use a rate basis of **Regular rate of pay** to calculate and pay the premium amount"},{"content":"A single earning code group can be shared by all earning codes that are used to calculate FLSA overtime premiums.","pos":[6998,7111]},{"pos":[7116,7149],"content":"Defining premium earning policies","linkify":"Defining premium earning policies","nodes":[{"content":"Defining premium earning policies","pos":[0,33]}]},{"content":"Every legal entity that pays premium earnings that are based on earning codes, or on characteristics of the worker or position, must be assigned to a premium earning policy.","pos":[7150,7323]},{"content":"You can create one policy that is shared by all legal entities, or you can create separate policies for each legal entity.","pos":[7324,7446]},{"content":"You can also use a combined approach.","pos":[7447,7484]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Tip:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> After a premium policy is created, it usually doesn't require additional maintenance.","pos":[7485,7579],"source":"**Tip:** After a premium policy is created, it usually doesn't require additional maintenance."},{"content":"You manage the premiums that your organization pays by maintaining the policy rules and earning codes.","pos":[7580,7682]},{"content":"Later in this process, you will define policy rule types and create policy rules for this policy.","pos":[7683,7780]},{"content":"The policy rules specify the conditions that must be met for the premium to be paid.","pos":[7781,7865]},{"content":"The policy rule types are used on the premium codes to associate the policy rules with the earning codes that are used to calculate the premium amount.","pos":[7866,8017]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Although you can't delete policies or policy rules, you can retire them so that they are no longer used.","pos":[8018,8132],"source":"**Note:** Although you can't delete policies or policy rules, you can retire them so that they are no longer used."},{"content":"When you retire a policy, you also retire all the corresponding policy rules for that policy.","pos":[8133,8226]},{"content":"You can't reactivate a policy that has been retired.","pos":[8227,8279]},{"content":"However, you can reactivate a retired policy rule by changing the effective dates on the rule.","pos":[8280,8374]},{"pos":[8379,8430],"content":"Setting up premiums that are based on earning codes","linkify":"Setting up premiums that are based on earning codes","nodes":[{"content":"Setting up premiums that are based on earning codes","pos":[0,51]}]},{"content":"These premiums are used for shift differentials and similar premiums that should be paid any time that specified earning codes are included on an earnings statement.","pos":[8431,8596]},{"content":"Before you create the premium earning codes, review the earning codes that were created during the basic Payroll setup process, to make sure that all earning codes that qualify for premiums have been created.","pos":[8597,8805]},{"content":"For example, your company pays a premium for hours that are worked on the second shift.","pos":[8806,8893]},{"content":"Earnings for the first shift and the second shift are 